<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-466  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 466.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  March 28 1990 n129 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM pushes Adobe fonts across SAA platforms. (IBM adopts AdobeType 1 font technology for Systems Application Architecture)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (planning).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     FontsImaging TechnologySAAStrategic PlanningPage Description Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM pushes Adobe fonts across SAA platforms IBM is to provide Adobe Systemsfont technology across its range of SAA platforms.andP;  The announcement comesfive months after Microsoft and Apple said they would offer a product thatwould rival Adobe's PostScript (News, issue 117).andM;The move can be seen as a minor victory for Adobe whose domination of thefont arena, with its PostScript standard, had been threatened by theMicrosoft/Apple venture.andP;  With this announcement, IBM has decided to stand onneutral ground and offer both technologies in certain versions of OS/2.andM;IBM says its decision is based on a review of customer requirements andpreferences.andP;  According to US analysts, there are approximately half amillion.andP;  PostScript printers currently installed.andM;Sue Thexton, Adobe national distribution manager, believes that the move willprevent confusion.andP;  &quot;It provides the user with a standard on whateverplatform he is using,&quot; he said.andP;  SAA-compliant operating systems includeOS/2, OS/400, VM and MVS.andM;OS/2 supports an open font interface that allows support for multiple fonttechnologies, providing users with a choice.andP;  &quot;It's healthy competition.andO;It's now up to the user to decide which fonts to use,&quot; said Thexton.andM;In an attempt to push its technology, Microsoft is to bundle TrueType withits version of OS/2 PM and Windows sometime this year.andP;  &quot;Microsoft would'veliked TrueType to be the only font imaging technology in OS/2,&quot; a companyspokesman said, &quot;but it expects to get wide software support for TrueType.&quot;andM;WordPerfect and Aldus are already working on making their softwareTrueType-compatible.andO;</TEXT></DOC>